    <!-- Telling a Customer No Section -->
                <p> <a href="https://beautifullydelicate.files.wordpress.com/2014/09/istock_hiding_behind_desk-70112828.jpg"><h1>Telling a customer "no"</h1></a></p> 
                <br>
                <p>"One of the most dreaded things to have to do when in customer service is being unable to grant the customer exactly what they want." </p>
                <p>A few years ago I held a position where I was constantly dealing with customers and orders they had placed online. The orders were for dress rentals; an order would be placed online for a dress to be delivered on a certain date and then returned in the mail (from the customer) four days after they received it.</p>
                <p>Every so often, I would need to deal with a customer that mistakenly entered inaccurate dates for them to receive their item.  Although it was result of their error, I still felt responsible for their overall experience which usually included some form of frustration (due to the error). When errors are made, no one benefits from the process. The key for me was ensuring that the proper steps were taken quickly, and without any extra frustration endured by the customer.  When a customer is upset they need someone to listen, to empathize with them, and walk them through the solution. </p>
                <p>On one occasion, a woman intended to have a dress delivered to her on a specific date, however, she mistakenly booked it for the following month. She called very anxious and demanded where her dress was. Upon review of her order, I informed her that it wasn’t supposed to be delivered until the following month. She immediately freaked out and began explaining that she would have never done that and that our system made the error. I took down all her information and told her I would quickly look into things and call her back within one hour. Unfortunately, the dress she had booked for the following month was not in the showroom (so I couldn’t even courier it to her quickly). I looked into her account, and had 3 similar dresses pulled for her in her size in hopes that we could send her those and she could choose one accordingly. I called her back to explain what we could do. Although she wasn't happy that her original choice was unavailable: she agreed, and also paid for the dresses to be couriered to her that day. A few days later she emailed me to thank me and apologized for her behavior. Even though the customer made the error, I did not feel comfortable with the experience and service she received. I offered her a 20% discount to put towards her next rental and included my contact information so I could ensure her next order went smoothly. </p>
                <p>That customer experience will always stay with me because she ended up being a repeat (and very happy) customer by the time I left. I think she appreciated the way I handled the situation, and the fact that I really wanted to ensure that she received good customer service regardless of who was at fault. </p>
